{
  "query": "What are the general effects on biodiversity of creating linear depressions or elevations on intertidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on multiple studies, creating linear depressions (grooves) and elevations (ridges/ledges) on intertidal artificial structures has varied effects on biodiversity. Linear depressions (groove habitats 1-50mm) show mixed effects on community composition, with two of three studies finding no alteration to combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition, though grooves supported species absent from structure surfaces without grooves (Action 3473). For species richness and diversity, three of six studies found that groove habitats increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and/or diversity, while two studies found no increase and one had mixed effects depending on site (Action 3473). Grooves supported higher species richness than small ridges or ledges created between them in some studies (Action 3473). Linear elevations (small ridges/ledges 1-50mm) generally showed less positive effects, with one of two studies finding no increase in combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness, and studies consistently finding that small ridges supported lower species richness than grooves created between them (Action 3464). Large ridges/ledges (>50mm) showed more positive results, with one of two studies reporting increased combined macroalgae, microalgae and invertebrate species diversity when combined with grooves and small protrusions (Action 3465). When grooves and small ridges/ledges are created together, six of 11 studies found increased species diversity and/or richness, while five studies had mixed effects depending on various factors including depth/height, shore level, and site (Action 3474). For population abundance, effects were similarly mixed, with some studies showing increased abundances while others showed no effect or mixed results depending on the specific organisms and environmental conditions (Actions 3473, 3464, 3465, 3474).",
